author: UCK4me2Xbz8mqhzn-B6WhSjQ
comment: Kolas i wouldn‚Äôt entirely say that as someone who is going into animal behaviour specifically reptile behaviour while I can never advocate for someone  doing something like in this video   Your claim isn‚Äôt necessarily entirely correct either.  Reptiles are actually only three steps removed from us in regards to behavior and as far as crocodilians are concerned there intellectual capacity isn‚Äôt far off from most of the domestic animals we keep.   Step one of removal is the human-animal gap this gap comes into play when humans have a difficult time relating to all animals due to the difference in our more complex behaviours   Step two, is the social-solitary gap.  Non social animals express emotions different than social animals. For example cats are solitary by nature and dogs are pack animals.  Step three is the mammal to reptile body language barrier. Mammals can pretty well universally read the body language of most other mammals, and we share many of the same body language cues. Reptiles have a fairly different set of body language tells   In order to form a relationship with a reptile you have to be able to find the bridge between these gaps in communication which isn‚Äôt easy   First you have to drop your expectation of complex Human-like behaviours.  Second you have to have experience in working with non social animal species.   Thirdly you need to have a at least base grasp of the animals individual body langue.     If you do this you can form a relationship  with them. It‚Äôs not the same relationship you have with a socially capable mammals species, however reptiles are fully able to express base emotions such as trust, contentment, and have the capability and mental capacity to associate another living thing as positive.   I‚Äôve worked with crocodile monitors before the second largest monitor species behind Komodo dragons. I formed a return ship with that animal, he had every chance to hurt me, and never took a single one.   He also clearly associated me as a positive aspect of his life as not only was I the only one able to work with him, he actively sought out my company when I made it available.

The character had his name; in one, he was a truck driver ( he loved trucks) in another he was a heavy-equipment operator, in another he was a cave-man, and one or two more. His guardian (absent parents) told me how much he enjoyed doing those assignments at night, compared to his usual homework.  The only problem is that it was quite time-intensive, writing a new story just for 1 kid, for each lesson. But if schools would invest in more teachersw and support workers , this kind of progress can be achieved. ,

author: UCGEYeDezIKZBtD-bU7hbDCA
comment: Thanks for mentioning the specific condition. I wasn't familiar with short-spine syndrome, and I was about to post an angry comment about how dog breeding is cruel abuse. So I looked up short-spine syndrome, and it's an extremely rare condition that affects less than 20 individual dogs worldwide. Unlike grossly deformed "breeds" like pugs and bulldogs, who thanks to generations of inbreeding spend their lives struggling to breathe through their squashed sinuses and trachea, short-spine syndrome doesn't seem to cause dogs extensive harm.   Unfortunately, the research does indicate that inbreeding is the root cause of the syndrome. So the same "purebred" dogs whose shallow gene pools grant them short lives plagued with conditions like arthritis, hip dysplasia and ingrown tails are also the ones most likely to wind up short-spined. It's good to know the condition is wildly uncommon and not as medically debilitating as brachycephaly, but it's still ultimately the result of humans conducting a crude eugenics experiment on animals because we decided certain deformities were cute and amusing.

comment: For anyone wondering "Why does that dog look like that?": It is a very rare condition known as Short Spine Syndrome; basically the vertebrae column stays in a cartilage form instead of hardening into bone, eventually the vertebraes start fusing together resulting in these silly looking dogs. author: UCCQ4ufQJObQ3CNzr18xQzJw
comment: @Ellen13 "Whoever created it _just_ took pictures and morphed them together to make them look like they're moving"? That's exactly what time lapses entale. And they ARE moving, for the record, a recorded video isnt anything else, just captured at a much faster rate (usually 30 or 60 images a second). The difference between taking photos and stitching them together afterwards, compared to just shooting a downright video, is that the overall quality is significantly enhanced. The average camera will take 1080p video, maybe 4k (albeit at a slower speed, worse colour range, many more things), while shooting photographs that are of resolutions like 5k, 6k, even 8k, a broad colour gamut, wider dynamic range... many technical terms that you won't get, I know, but basically: many improvements. Things dont get easier for video when it's shot in extremely dark conditions, like the auroras. The camera will artificially boost the video to make it brighter, but results in a grainy/noisy image that loses sharpness and detail. Meanwhile when you shoot many photos to make a video, you can take every single photo during several seconds, allowing you to capture light _over time_ instead of artificially boosting it, resulting in a clear, sharp, yet bright image. Sure, as a consequence of this, when stitched together, the video will look sped up, but will generally be much more pleasing to look at than a normal video. Now you tell me, would you have preferred to see what you saw, a great quality, sped up looking video, or a video like you saw here, noisy and grainy, feeling like 360 or 480p, blown up to a massive screen? Right, so quit being a bitch about it and appreciate what you got to see.  All of this ignoring that some photographer sat outside for hours taking that timelapse, in the dark, incredibly cold night, probably days or weeks on end, just for some unappreciative fuck to come around and uneducatedly criticise their work. Like yeah, auroras are pretty and all, but comfort-wise you wouldnt want that for yourself.

author: UCncWGtv1JuMH01zkaKxeZMA
comment: Actually, that shark has Hyperkyphosis, not Scoliosis.  There is a difference but they are very similar.  Hyperkyphosis is a posterior (backwards) abnormal curve in the spine.  Scoliosis is a lateral (sideways) abnormal curve in the spine.  If this shark had scoliosis, it would be protruding from it's side, not it's back.  I know this because I am a 3rd year Kinesiology student in University.

author: UCJq3StSNV2pc8k5aWjjfSfw
comment: I was with my dad when we saw a line of something like 80-100+ Satellites from Elon musk launch from Wisconsin and we were mind boggled as to what in the hell they were as we have never seen or heard of anything like it happening before especially near us and some of their patterns and shapes looked absolutely fucking alien when you looked close! And the speed at which they or at least certain ones moved and instantly changed directions in certain areas that shouldn't have been possible for any modern aircraft as they were at the very minimum multiple miles if not tens of miles away while looking like they were zipping around 10 times faster than the speed of sound when turning 180 degrees which should be impossible at that speed that fast due to momentum, aerodynamics, and how literally no human could do that without the g force killing them instantly then forcing their body to a puddle of mush even if their magical metal material didn't outright fold its wings and collapse the cockpit in on a center fold or something else.    Not sure If we saw the same starlink satellites or how many launch locations there were but when I saw those lights they were spread out quite a ways and WAAAAAY farther away than whatever this guy was seeing and it looked like they first went straight up and then started coming our direction (that could be due to perception though) there was also a few of those lights that were zipping around in a bunch of strange patterns and we live in an area where a bunch of jets and helicopters every now and then fly over to land some few tens of miles away some of which come pretty low considering we are 20 or so miles. I know normal flight patterns and those lights zipping around in patterns and some times hovering sure as hell were not normal commercial airplanes or helicopters. Not at those speeds and turning rates. When I looked squinting at it it had a very strange triangle shape or boomerang shape that changed constantly as I tried to look at it due to the distance and the strange light reflection. It was winter though so it could have been the frost/ice in the air causing it over that kind of extreme distance which is all the more reason to know the speed/turning rate was insane for that distance.   It will probably be the strangest sight I will ever see in the sky until I confirm a real alien spaceship with biological aliens then walking out of it with my own eyes.   WAAAY stranger and a stronger impact than what this guy had as I was shoveling snow on a roof and called out my dad and sister to see it!

author: UCHWX4pzjQsyrdZE3y6S7IDg
comment: 1:34 It is an "Ajolote" and is endemic from Mexico, the Aztecs saw a manifestation of the god Xolotl, who bring souls to the underworld along with the setting sun. Axolotls, like their European cousins, the olms, are neotenic, meaning that they reach sexual maturity looking like larvae;  retaining its gills and tail.  This causes that they do not develop physically, but they regenerate.  The axolotl, as it is also known, grow limbs, bones and organs that have been damaged or cut.  They are a thousand times more resistant to cancer than mammals.  If they survive modern threats long enough for us to understand their immune cells, we could make tremendous advances in numerous medical therapies. Currently, the axolotl is one of the many endangered species.

author: UC-p5ZJL97fVLtJ0S0N5n1kQ

comment: Just would like to say that yes, they are extremely endangered, but only in the wild, not as a whole species. As an axolotl owner, I can say that there are plenty of axolotls bred in captivity that keep the species as a whole from going extinct. Other than that, very accurate.

author: UCluPHWQL0yBMQo1hbPKB_Og
comment: About the sunbathing woman clip: I agree, it made me uncomfortable, too. I don't know exactly in which country this was. But I have seen a video of a white woman with shiny blonde hair visiting what I believe was China and a large group of young Chinese girls gawk over her and crowd her, asking her for a group picture with her. They were very intrigued and excited to have met this woman, even though she was not a celebrity (I think). I asked my Indian boyfriend why they were so excited and he says that it happens all the time in that part of the world. I'm not saying India or Sri Lanka or Bangladesh is the same as China or Japan or Korea. But a good portion of those citizens have probably only seen white or black people on TV, and we can't expect the whole world to behave the same way Westerners do. A visiting traveler might think it's weird but they may not. That might be why those men felt at liberty to behave that way.

comment: @oceanexploration great explanation! but when I was practicing spin recoveries in both gliders and Cessnas using the ailerons (well crossed controls - like turn left while pedal right)  is what gets you into the spin. (A spin is when one wing is more stalled than the other) the recovery procedure was: neutral the ailerons (Center the ‚Äústeering wheel‚Äù) and then use the rudder (foot pedals) in the opposite direction of the turn to break the spin. Then recover from straight stall or dive, and finally: unclench ;)  Ps they teach this because inexperienced pilots can unwittingly get into spins when landing if trying to do too many things to line up the runway. Up high you have enough space to get back out, but near the ground this can be fatal. So practice practice!  The rest of your explanation was plausible. But very strange that the pilot lost control. Maybe it was intentional? Or negligence‚Ä¶ on-purpose makes sense to me because spins (if recovery is safe) are suuuuuper fun and the pilot could have been dicking around ¬Ø\_(„ÉÑ)_/¬Ø but I‚Äôm totally guessing at this point.

comment: 2:04 for anyone wondering, that is called a trap door spider (for obvious reasons) They dig a burrow about 5 inches or so deep then cover the entrance with a little door made from tightly wound silk. They use their burrow as both a place to live and a way to catch prey. They sit and peek out the door and pounce on an unsuspecting bug who was unfortunate enough to happen by then pull them back into their burrow.

author: UC9HIq4e9zG8vh1z3dx_0Xxg
comment: Many reptiles can brumate actually! The only difference is that with most lizards and snakes, you don't put them in a fridge or such.   You could simply lower their tank temperature for the winter or sometimes even just a few weeks. It does take more experience, but its really helpful for someone who has lots of reptiles. Over the period you dont have to feed the reptile, and this helps me especially around Christmas because I will have extra money to spend on family and such :)  Not every reptile, and not every turtle/tortoise can brumate, but a good majority can.   Its normal and wont harm the animal in anyway if done correctly.

author: UCAk5Tiedq8L9Rw1mKXkKF5g
comment: I love the spite with which you said "No, this is not animal abuse"   FYI though, don't just stick your turtle into a freezing refrigerator. You have to make the temperature drop very slowly and make sure they don't have anything in their digestive system so it doesn't rot. But yeah, brumation is not dangerous. Just look up how to do it properly before doing it, and consider if it's even something you want to do to begin with. People generally do it for breeding, since turtles are perfectly happy without brumating.

To add to the embarrassment, I was at the wrong delivery address.  Now I can't shake the habit of peaking through the window to triple check the car is in park.  EDIT: Just to clear things up. I put it in neutral instead of park and shut the car off. The car didn't start rolling backwards until I got to the house door. It rolled down the driveway about 6 feet until it hit grass. Nothing major, but enough to give me a heart attack. Also this was about 2 weeks after I got my license.

author: UCzFQAYRJXO1-bxPLukjiVGA
comment: Your theory might be true. Good idea! However, moths are _not_ attracted to light for that reason. This was recently disproven (for the most part), on the grounds that if moths were using the light-source as a tracking point, they would circularize the target, changing yaw but not pitch (On a vertical light). Since moths change roll, pitch and yaw and even circularization direction, it's been concluded that mist likely they're not using the light-source/moon for tracking.  Remember, there's no such thing as settled science, so if new data comes up, this may be subject to change. For now though, most people agree the moon-tracking thing is incorrect though.

author: UC7JqkY-ov0k-Nzxl6fifycw
comment: 0:55 Here are some of the standard advises taught in every Japanese elementary school. If you are in sturdy building like this, first thing you‚Äôll do is to hide under the table and wait till the earthquake stops. It‚Äôs not recommended to start evacuating in a rush at this point, because all sorts of unexpected things can happen while the ground is still shaking (toppling at dangerous places, getting hit by falling objects, crushing hard into other people etc). Turn off fire and gas before hiding if you are in the kitchen, because major part of the earthquake-related death is caused by fire. Open the door if it happened to be close around, so that you can prevent getting locked up in case the door frame deformed. When you evacuate, no one should run but walk. Panicked cloud is often more lethal than the earthquake itself.

author: UCMn-nSlLI7kCb7wVlatzbDg
comment: 0:57 for those who are confused, what they were doing here is filling the tire with flammable liquid, then setting it on fire. What this does is it rapidly causes the air to expand, filling up the tire. The reason this works only on really flat tires is Because the tire is so flat, the tube is pushed up against the wheel, and because the tube is made of rubber it, has a body of its own and stays in the circle, which breaks the seal that the tire normally has on the wheel, so the air has a place to rush in. Once the tire fills up, the tire is no longer pushed up against the wheel and it seals back up again, so the air can‚Äôt get out.

author: UCFBVkzG0SbI8coFpgbwI-NQ
comment: @Lost Colony of KEKkoslovakia Sure, the manufacturer is responsible for quality control. But they are only responsible for the product's quality up to the standard set by the ordering company's budget. If you give a maker 10$ to create your product, don't expect the maker to spend 9$ on material, free labor, and guaranteed master craftsmanship. So ultimately EVERYONE is responsible for a product's quality. As a consumer, before blaming a product's country of manufacture, try investigating the product's cost of production, cost of manufacture, advertising budget, profit, etc. Don't label developing countries for producing poor quality products, when the original design company already exploits cheap labor/cost of material for massive profits, and don't forget as a consumer, you're also paying for all of their advertisements, brand name value, and all the other sugar-coated premiums that you may not even know about
